// Census tabulation bottleneck
// 1880 census: 50 million people
// Clerks: 1,500
// Time: 8 years
// Cost: $5.8 million
// 
// 1890 projection: 62 million people
// At same rate: 10+ years
// Problem: Census must complete in <10 years

// Hollerith tabulator operation
// Input: Punch card (45 columns)
// 
// For each card:
//   1. Press pins down onto card
//   2. Pins through holes contact mercury
//   3. Completed circuits increment counters
//   4. Sorting electromagnets open correct bin
//   5. Card drops into sorted compartment
// 
// Speed: ~80 cards/minute
// Accuracy: Near-perfect (electrical, not human)

// Punch card encoding (simplified)
// Column 1-2: Age (00-99)
// Column 3: Sex (M/F = 1/0)
// Column 4-5: State code (01-50)
// Column 6-8: Occupation code
// ...
// 
// Binary principle:
// Hole punched = 1 (circuit complete)
// No hole = 0 (circuit open)
// 
// This IS binary data storage!

// Zuse's key innovations
// 
// Binary arithmetic:
//   Why use 10 states when 2 will do?
//   Relays are naturally binary (on/off)
// 
// Floating-point:
//   Separate mantissa and exponent
//   Handle very large and very small numbers
//   (Standard IEEE 754 wouldn't exist until 1985)
// 
// Stored programs:
//   Instructions on punched film
//   The machine reads what to do next

